Carboxylesterase Proteins Analysis - Skyler Liu

Introduction

Scientific Question

How do the sequences and different types of bonding contribute to the structural similarities and differences between the 2H7C and 2HRQ (Homo sapien) and the 5MIF (Tuber melanosporum) carboxylesterase protein structures?

Carboxylesterases are enzymes that hydrolyze carboxylesters into their corresponding alcohol and carboxylic acid. These enzymes are important for detoxification and have been identified in all living organisms (Hatfield, 2016). In the black Perigord truffle (Tuber melanosporum), carboxylesterases are preferentially expressed during their symbiotic phase as this type of fungus has a mutualistic relationship with its host (Cavazzini, 2017). Unlike truffles, humans do not have mutualistic host relationships and instead, carboxylesterases can be used to metabolize drugs such as cocaine and heroin (Bencharit, 2006). In different species, carboxylesterases have different uses. In this project, I wanted to look at the bonds and the 5MIF structure contains cis-peptide bonds while the 2H7C and 2HRQ structures contain disulfide bridges. Cis-peptide bonds are found primarily in bends and turns but provide unfavorable contacts between adjacent amino acid residues (Stewart, 1990). On the other hand, disulfide bridges are formed specifically in between cysteine residues and are fundamental to the biological processes of the protein (Wiedemann, 2020). I chose two human carboxylesterase proteins that were bound in compounds because I want to know whether being in a compound would also affect the protein structure and binding.

Scientific Hypothesis

If the FASTA and pdb sequences for 2H7C, 5MIF, and 2HRQ are aligned and the protein structure models are compared, then the amount and locations of their bonds between which amino acids can be determined and show how they contribute to the structural differences between species.

The first bioinformatics method that will be used is a pairw ise sequence alignment of the FASTA files which will be retrieved from the EMBL-EBI database. Multiple sequence alignment can be used to compare the conserved and variable sequences of carboxylesterases between the two species. In order to display this information, a sequence logo will be used with larger letters indicating conserved amino acids. The next bioinformatics method will be structural bioinformatics with data obtained from the Protein Databank to review the two different protein structures. 3-D protein measurements will also be used to visualize the proteins and their bonds.

Package Descriptions

The packages that I will be needing include are below. How I installed the packages if I didnt already have them was to go to the Tools tab and select Install Packages in the drop down menu. Then, I typed in the name of the package I wanted and hit the Install button. All of the packages below can be installed using that method. The packages can also be installed in chunk or the console with the install.packages() function but I use the other method to keep my workspace relatively free of clutter. Then, use the library() function to read in the packages.

BioStrings: I will use Biostrings to read in the FASTA files.

BiocManager: I will be using BiocManager for multiple sequence analysis to align the sequences.

msa: This is a BiocManager package that is needed for multiple sequence alignment specifically. I will be using the BiocManager package msa specifically for multiple sequence alignment.

ggseqlogo: I will be using ggseqlogo to create the sequence logos.

bio3d: I will be using bio3d for structural bioinformatics analysis.

NGLViewR: I will be using NGLViewR for visually displaying the protein structures.

Multiple Sequence Alignment

# FASTA files obtained from EMBL-EBI. Read in FASTA files.

all_FASTA <- c(FASTA_5MIF, FASTA_2H7C, FASTA_2HRQ)

pwa <- msaMuscle(all_FASTA)

print(pwa, show = "complete")

3-D Protein Measurements

The package NGLViewR will be used to view the proteins structures in 3-D in R without the need for PyMOL.

# Load in the protein structure. 
NGLVieweR("5MIF") %>%
  addRepresentation("cartoon") %>%
  # Show these residues and bonds to distinguish them from the cartoon ribbon structure. 
  addRepresentation("ball+stick", param = list(
    colorScheme = "element",
    colorValue = "yellow",
    sele = "55 or 56 or 151 or 152 or 156 or 157"
  )) %>%
  # Contact: specifically shows contact between residues. 
   addRepresentation("contact",
    param = list(
      name = "contact",
      sele = "55 or 56 or 151 or 152 or 156 or 157",
      filterSele = list("55 or 56 or 151 or 152 or 156 or 157"),
      labelVisible = TRUE,
      labelFixedSize = FALSE,
      ionicInteraction = TRUE,
      cisPeptide = TRUE, 
      labelUnit = "angstrom", # "", "angstrom", "nm"
      labelSize = 2
    )) %>%
  # Add labels for easier viewing and identification. 
  addRepresentation("label",
    param = list(
      sele = "55 or 56 or 151 or 152 or 156 or 157",
      labelType = "format",
      labelFormat = "[%(resname)s]%(resno)s", # or enter custom text
      labelGrouping = "residue", # or "atom" (eg. sele = "20:A.CB")
      color = "white",
      fontFamiliy = "sans-serif",
      xOffset = 1,
      yOffset = 0,
      zOffset = 0,
      fixedSize = TRUE,
      radiusType = 1,
      radiusSize = 1.5, # Label size
      showBackground = FALSE
      # backgroundColor="black",
      # backgroundOpacity=0.5
    )
  )

Analysis of Results

Based on the first 50 amino acids aligned visualized in the sequence logo, it was surprising that the 5MIF and 2HRQ sequences had more conserived amino acids despite the 2HRQ and 2H7C sequences both being human sequences. The 5MIF sequence was also much shorter than the other two but that can be explained by the structure consisting of fewer subunits as the human proteins are bound in complexes to stabilize them. The cis-peptide bonds identified in the 3-D protein measurements of 5MIF allow the structure to have cyclic symmetry as they can bind to different amino acids. The disulfide bridges identified in the 3-D protein measurements only occur betwen cysteines and also contribute to the dihedral symmetry both human protein structures have.
